## AI Agent Integration

This CLI supports two integration methods for AI agents. **You only need one** - choose based on your use case.

### Option 1: Session Hooks (Recommended for Custom Integrations)

Session hooks provide bidirectional communication with the CLI, enabling rich context sharing and state management. This is ideal for custom agent integrations that need deep integration with the CLI.

**Benefits:**
- Bidirectional communication
- Rich context sharing
- State management
- Custom integration flexibility

**Use when:**
- You need custom agent integration
- You require bidirectional communication
- You need state management
- You're building a custom agent framework

See session hook documentation for implementation details.

### Option 2: Agent Skills (Recommended for Standard Discovery)

Agent skills enable discovery via [agentskills.io](https://agentskills.io). This provides static documentation for agent understanding without runtime integration.

**Benefits:**
- Standard discovery mechanism
- No runtime integration required
- Simple to implement
- Ideal for agents that support skill discovery

**Use when:**
- You want standard discovery
- You don't need runtime integration
- You're using agents that support skill discovery
- You want simple documentation-based integration

#### Generating SKILL.md

To generate the skill documentation:

```bash
{{ project_slug }} skill --generate
```

This creates a `SKILL.md` file in the current directory with comprehensive documentation for AI agents.

#### Validating SKILL.md

To check if the skill file is up to date:

```bash
{{ project_slug }} skill --check
```

This command is used in CI/CD pipelines to ensure the skill file stays synchronized with the CLI.

#### CI/CD Integration

The boilerplate includes a GitHub Actions workflow (`.github/workflows/skill-check.yml`) that automatically validates the skill file on every push and pull request. The workflow will fail if the committed skill file is stale.

To update a stale skill file:

```bash
{{ project_slug }} skill --generate
git add SKILL.md
git commit -m "Update skill file"
```

## Choosing Between Hook and Skill

| Feature | Session Hooks | Agent Skills |
|---------|--------------|--------------|
| Bidirectional Communication | ✅ | ❌ |
| State Management | ✅ | ❌ |
| Standard Discovery | ❌ | ✅ |
| Runtime Integration | ✅ | ❌ |
| Documentation-Based | ❌ | ✅ |
| Implementation Complexity | Higher | Lower |

**Recommendation:** Start with Agent Skills for simple use cases. Use Session Hooks only if you need bidirectional communication or state management.

